 England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Riby (Lincs) or perhaps Ribby (Lancs); on the latter name,  see also  Rigby  . See also   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rigby","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Ribby in Lancashire, named with Old Scandanavian <i>hryggr</i> ‘ridge’ + <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’. Compare   Rigsby  ."]},{"name":"Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames","meanings":["1  Irish: from  <b>Ó Ráighne</b>,  <b>Mac Ráighne</b>, from a personal name derived from the Scandinavian name  <i>Rǫgnvaldr</i>. Compare English   Randall  ,   Reynold  .","2  Norman, English: locative name from Regny (Loire).","3  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Rayn(e)y</i>,  <i>Renie</i>, a pet form of   Reynold  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":20,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":29,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Driby was born in 1195, in Stratfield Mortimer, Berkshire, England, his father, Simon Driby, was 21 and his mother, Mrs Simon Driby, was 21. He married Andrina of Berkshire in 1220, in Stratfield Mortimer, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1245, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1195–1245":"1195–1245","1205–1249":"1205–1249","1225–1289":"1225–1289","1232–Male":"1232–Surnud","–1275":"–1275","1175–1215":"1175–1215","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","Aft 1225":"pärast 1225","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1175":"1175","1195":"1195","after 1215":"pärast 1215","1249":"1249","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1289":"1289","1232":"1232","about 1232":"umbes 1232","Stratfield Mortimer, Berkshire, England":"Stratfield Mortimer, Berkshire, England","England":"England","Wokefield, Stratfield Mortimer, Berkshire, England":"Stratfield Mortimer, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tumby, Lincolnshire, England":"Tumby, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1195–1245":"1195–1245","1205–1249":"1205–1249","1225–1289":"1225–1289","1232–Male":"1232–Kuollut","–1275":"–1275","1175–1215":"1175–1215","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut","Aft 1225":"1225 jälkeen","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1175":"1175","1195":"1195","after 1215":"1215 jälkeen","1249":"1249","1